// Function to check if a domain has a valid TLD
function hasValidTLD(domain) {
    const parts = domain.split('.').reverse();
    let domainTLD = parts[0];

    for (let i = 1; i < parts.length; i++) {
        domainTLD = parts[i] + '.' + domainTLD;
        if (tlds.includes(domainTLD)) {
            return true;
        }
    }

    return false;
}

// Function to manually extract the hostname from a URL
function getHostnameFromUrl(url) {
    // Remove protocol (http, https, ftp, etc.)
    let hostname = url.indexOf("://") > -1 ? url.split('/')[2] : url?.split('/')[0];

    // Remove port number and path
    hostname = hostname.split(':')[0].split('?')[0];

    return hostname;
}

// Function to extract domain from any URL type
function extractDomainFromURL(url) {
    const hostname = getHostnameFromUrl(url);
    const hostnameParts = hostname.split('.').reverse();
    let domain = '';
    let potentialTLD = hostnameParts[0];

    for (let i = 1; i < hostnameParts.length; i++) {
        potentialTLD = hostnameParts[i] + '.' + potentialTLD;

        if (tlds.includes(potentialTLD)) {
            // Check if there's another part before the TLD
            if (i + 1 < hostnameParts.length) {
                domain = hostnameParts[i + 1] + '.' + potentialTLD;
                break;
            }
        }
    }

    // Handle cases where the URL is just a second-level domain with standard TLD
    if (!domain && hostnameParts.length > 1 && tlds.includes(hostnameParts[0])) {
        domain = hostnameParts[1] + '.' + hostnameParts[0];
    }

    return domain || null;
}

// Function to extract domain from an email address
function extractDomainFromEmail(email) {
    const parts = email.split('@');
    if (parts.length === 2) {
        return parts[1];
    }
    return null;
}

// Function to check if a domain is from a free mail provider
function isFreeMailProvider(domain) {
    return freeMailProviders.includes(domain);
}

// Function to process input (either URL or Email)
function processInput(input) {
    let domain = null;
    let isFreeMail = false;

    if (input.includes('@') && input.split('@').length === 2) {
        // Handle as email
        domain = extractDomainFromEmail(input);
    } else {
        // Handle as URL
        domain = extractDomainFromURL(input);
    }

    if (domain) {
        isFreeMail = isFreeMailProvider(domain);
    }

    return {
        input,
        domain,
        free_mail_provider: isFreeMail
    };
}

## Read Me

This node is designed to cleanse URLs and extract their domain names efficiently. 

It effectively handles a wide range of URL formats, including those with unconventional or complex top-level domains (TLDs), such as 'co.uk'.

You can also use it to extract the domain from an email. The node will also check if the domain is from a free email provider (gmail.com / outlook.com...etc) or not.

### How It Works
The node analyzes the provided URL, removing any unnecessary elements.

It then identifies and extracts the domain name, ensuring compatibility with a diverse array of TLDs.

The node utilizes an extensive list of TLDs to guarantee accurate domain extraction for virtually any URL. 

To view the complete list of supported top-level domains, please visit: [TLD List on GitHub](https://github.com/publicsuffix/list)


### How to use it
Call this workflow using the "execute workflow" node

You can pass either an email variable or a url variable. 

For email, the node also detect free mail provider such as Yahoo / Google...etc
